+# Compute-optimal phase-grid review
+
+The phase-grid results support the compute-optimal visible-spectrum theorem.
+
+## Current saturating case
+
+For `a=1.5, b=1.4`, the phase boundary is
+
+```text
+theta_c = 2(1 - b/a) ≈ 0.133.
+```
+
+Thus only `theta=0` is time-limited; all tested `theta >= 0.25` are already in
+the variance-limited phase.  The observed risk exponent saturates near `-1/6`,
+matching the theorem.
+
+## Hard full-range case
+
+For `a=3.0, b=1.4`, the whole interval `theta in [0,1]` remains time-limited.
+The observed compute-risk exponent improves monotonically as theta increases,
+from about `0.102` at `theta=0` to about `0.167` at `theta=1`, matching the
+predicted trend.
+
+## Fixed weight decay
+
+The fixed `delta=1e-3` and `delta=1e-4` rows should not be compared to the
+no-weight-decay exponents.  Fixed weight decay imposes a fixed learned-mode cap
+and therefore an asymptotic source-bias floor.  The observed small negative risk
+slopes are finite-range transients toward that floor.
+
+The follow-up theorem `notes/20_compute_optimal_weight_decay_scaling.md` derives
+the correct law for schedules `delta(C)=C^{-s}`.  The experiment
+`experiments/compute_optimal_weight_decay_schedule.py` checks the transition from
+fixed-decay floors to recovered no-decay scaling.
